<HEADLINE>
<P>
KENNEDY WASTES NO TIME POUNDING PAVEMENT FOR JOB 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By from Staff and Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Former Taft High catcher Kevin Kennedy, fired Wednesday as manager of the 
Texas Rangers, interviewed Thursday for the manager's job of the Boston Red 
Sox. 
</P>
<P>
 "Kevin has excellent baseball credentials and he received extraordinary 
training," Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Red Sox, who fired manager Butch Hobson on Sept. 20, said they will 
continue to interview managerial candidates, although no other names were 
mentioned. 
</P>
<P>
 Kennedy, 40, was dismissed after finishing the abbreviated season with a 52-62 
record, first in the AL West.  
</P>
<P>
 He was 138-138 in two seasons with Texas. 
</P>
<P>
 Before that, he held various coaching jobs in the Los Angeles Dodger and 
Montreal Expo organizations. 
</P>
<P>
 Kennedy, who played three seasons at San Diego State and eight years in the 
minor leagues, was the fourth manager to be fired since the players went on 
strike Aug. 12. 
</P>
<P>
 The Rangers had lost six in a row before the strike, and their lead over 
Oakland had been cut to one game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
